Statelessness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Session continuation protocols for HTTP must allow for stateless implementation
 on the server side, at least when TLS is used.
 This means that any state must be encrypted and encoded into a session
 state cookie that is re
\change_inserted -733538347 1355691103
-
\change_unchanged
sent by the client to the server on every request.
 The server, of course, must be the one to assign such state, and it must
 use an encryption key known only by the server.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that statelessness implies that there is no way to implement replay
 protection
\change_inserted -733538347 1355691143

\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\change_inserted -733538347 1355691170
No, it means that replay protection is optional - the server chooses whether
 it wants it or not
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\end_inset


\change_unchanged
.
 In the case of session continuation with TLS this is not a concern because
 TLS itself protects against replays.
 But when session continuation is used without TLS then statelessness really
 does mean that there can be no replay protection (of course, this is also
 thus with web cookies).
\end_layout

